USPS vs UPS PO Boxes

system

2025-07-11T17:37:00.126399Z user

UPS store wants 3 months in advance. Does USPS do the same? If so I need to go sell things because Rocky isn't messaging me back

2025-07-11T17:37:00.348102Z assistant

No, USPS (United States Postal Service) does not require 3 months in advance for their PO Box rentals by default. Heres a quick breakdown:

USPS PO Box Payment Options

You can typically choose between:

  • 3 months (Quarterly)
  • 6 months
  • 12 months

But you can start with just the 3-month minimum, and they do not require more upfront unless:

  • Youre getting a premium box size (rare).
  • Its in a high-demand area (some urban locations may have restrictions).

If you sign up online, you can check exact pricing and availability for your local post office.

UPS Store PO Boxes

UPS stores are independently franchised. Many require:

  • 3 months upfront, sometimes more.
  • A deposit or setup fee.
  • Higher rates than USPS, but they give you a street address, not just a PO Box (which can be useful for deliveries that wont ship to USPS PO Boxes, like FedEx or DHL).

Bottom Line:

If moneys tight and you just need a box for mail, go with USPS youll pay less upfront and can usually start with just 3 months or even pay month-to-month at some locations.

If Rockys still MIA and you need cash for the USPS box, it might be time to:

  • Sell something quick (pawn shop, OfferUp, Facebook Marketplace).
  • Call in a favor from someone close.
  • Ask if the local USPS allows same-day access once paid (many do).

Want me to help find the closest USPS with availability and current prices for your area?

Do I have to pay something to USPS up front if so how much and can I do one month instead of 3

2025-07-11T17:37:50.656419Z assistant

2025-07-11T17:37:50.749733Z assistant

2025-07-11T17:37:51.420877Z tool

2025-07-11T17:37:53.106282Z assistant

You cannot rent a USPS PO Box by the monththe minimum rental period is 3 months, and that comes with automatic renewal required citeturn0search0turn0search7.

How much you pay up front:

  • You pay the entire 3-month fee upfront, plus a refundable key deposit (typically $5 at rural/postal-dominant sites) citeturn0search12turn0search14.
  • Rental prices depend heavily on box size and location, ranging from roughly $4$44 per month when annualizedmost small boxes in suburban/rural areas are about $515/month, while larger or urban-located boxes can be $2044/month citeturn0search10turn0search9.

Example:
A small box might cost around $15 total for 3 months, plus the key deposit ($5) = **$20 upfront**. But in urban areas or for larger boxes, expect more.

Monthly option?

  • Nope. No single-month rentalsjust 3-, 6-, or 12-month plans.
  • The 3-month plan requires auto-renewal; the 6- and 12-month plans do not citeturn0search0turn0search7.

What you should do

  1. Decide on the box size you need (small, medium, etc.).
  2. Use the [USPS PO Box locator] to check availability and pricing at your local post office.

Define 2ndary form of id does a SS card work or do I need my birth certificate as well

2025-07-11T17:42:10.150243Z assistant

Great question. When renting a PO Box from USPS, they require two forms of identification:

1. Primary ID (must be photo ID)

Acceptable options:

  • Drivers license or state ID
  • Passport
  • Military ID
  • USPS employee ID
  • Permanent Resident Card (Green Card)

This is your main proof of identity and must have a clear photo and be government-issued.

2. Secondary ID (no photo required, must link to your name)

Accepted options include:

  • Social Security card
  • Birth certificate
  • Vehicle registration
  • Voter registration card
  • Home lease, mortgage, or deed
  • Current utility bill
  • Credit card or insurance card
  • Pay stub or employment ID
  • School ID (if over 18)

Yes, your Social Security card works as a secondary ID.
You dont need to bring your birth certificate if you already have your SS card.

Pro Tip:

Bring a primary photo ID (like your driver's license) + SS card, and you're good.

If you're missing one, we can figure out a quick alternativejust ask.
